Basis for Model

The basis for the experimental model is Expectation-Maximization of the Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM). Here, we will detail several experiments that show that our model works through data-driven simulations, demonstrate the adjustments to GMM that we make, show that they work for simulation data, and finally investigate how the experimental data fits the model.

Basic Gaussian Mixture Model

The basic Gaussian Mixture Model hinges on Expectation-Maximization, a process for finding a locally maximizing fit for mixed distributions of the exponential family. GMM has 2 steps, the expectation (or responsibility) step, and the maximization step, and repeats until our log likelihood converges.

Experimental Model (time-variant GMM, tGMM)

For our experiment, we have task fMRI data in which test subjects have a task presented before them at known points in time. We theorize that the latent signals driving thinking patterns can be represented by a gaussian mixture, and that we can adjust EM to predict the covariance matrices of each experimental task condition. We define our density function of an observed \(x\) of some latent signal \(z\):

\begin{equation} p(x_i) = \sum_{c} \pi_{ic} N(x_i | \mu_c, \Sigma_c) \end{equation}

Using our predicted covariance matrices for each experimental task condition, we can then use the Wilcoxon signed-rank test to find rois that show differential activity based on task condition.

tGMM Framework

E Step

Like traditional GMM, our expectation step consists of computing the responsibilities of each potential cluster on our individual data points. \begin{equation} r_{ic} = \frac{\pi_{ic}N(x | \mu_c, \Sigma_c)}{\sum_{c'}\pi_{ic'}N(x | \mu_{c'}, \Sigma_{c'})} \end{equation}

where \(r_ic\) represents the given responsibility of a cluster \(c\) on time point \(i\). This is a relatively intuitive process, as we are essentially considering the probability that a given data point is a member of a cluster and normalizing by the probability that it is in any of the clusters.

M Step

Again, much of our process here will look very similar to traditional GMM. As we have information about how the task conditions evolve over time, however, we can skip prediction of the \(\pi\) vector entirely. To define some \(\rho\) vector, we can convolve a spike train \(f\) of condition onsets with a response function that gives the expected proportion of signal at each successive timestep after an impulse, such that:

\begin{equation} \rho_{c} = f_c(i)*h(i) \end{equation}

For each condition \(c\), and where \(\rho_c\) is defined for each timestep \(i\). We normalize our \(\rho\) vector to sum to 1 at each time point, calling the normalized vector \(\pi\):

\begin{equation} \pi_{ic} = \frac{\rho_{ic}}{\sum_c' \rho_{ic'}} \end{equation}

and now our model is simply a time-variant adaptation of GMM.

The cumulative responsibility of a given cluster \(c\)

\begin{equation} m_c = \sum_i r_{ic} \end{equation} For updated means. The logic behind the mean maximization is that we consider how much a particular cluster “explains” our \(i\)th data point, so \(\mu\) is more strongly impacted by data points that it explains more effectively. \begin{equation} \hat{\mu_c} = \frac{1}{m_c} \sum_i r_{ic}x_i \end{equation} For updating the covariances. The logi here is again the same; if a point is explained well by a particular distribution, its covariance is more strongly considered than if it isn’t explained by that distribution. \begin{equation} \hat{\Sigma_c} = \frac{1}{m_c} \sum_i r_{ic}(x_i - \hat{\mu_c})^T(x_i - \hat{\mu_c}) \end{equation}

We repeat the expectation and maximization steps until we reach convergence of the likelihood (and consequently the log likelihood) of our predicted clusters matching our data.

\begin{equation} log(p(X)) = \sum_i log[\sum_c \pi_{ic} N(x_i | \mu_c, \Sigma_c)] \end{equation}

Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test

Here, the data is clearly paired, as we would expect a relationship between correlation values taken at the within-subject level, and the within-scan level. We do not want to impose parametricity for the covariance values being analyzed, so we proceed with the non-parametric wilcoxon signed-rank test.

Real Data Exploratory Analysis

To begin, we demonstrate some formal proofs-of-concept of our idea on the real data. First, we must demonstrate that time periods we denote as particular conditions actually show differening covariance and means. Note that we skip loading and sourcing operations for simplicity, and pick up our function assuming that we have loaded our timeseries successfully:

  ## Condition Onset/Correlation ---------------------------------------------------
  cond_key <- c("Relational", "Locational", "Incorrect")
  onsets <- get_trial_onsets(infopath, ts, subs, runs, onset_cat=c(1,1,2,2,1,1,2,2,3), cond_key=cond_key)
  onset_times <- onsets$times
  conditions <- onsets$conditions
  
  # Rectangular window
  #fx <- c(0,1,1,1,1,0)
  # Asymmetric Window
  fx <- array(rev(c(0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0)))
  
  # replace incorrect with overall, to get a better sampling of the data
  pi_vecs <- convolve_trial_onsets(onset_times, fx)
  pi_vecs <- sapply(pi_vecs, function(sub) {
     sub[,3] <- rep(1, length=dim(sub)[1])
     return(sub)
  }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  cond_key <- c("Relational", "Locational", "Overall")
  
  pi_vecs_cond <- sapply(names(pi_vecs), function(sub) {
    pi_vec <- alply(pi_vecs[[sub]], 2)
    names(pi_vec) <- cond_key
    return(pi_vec)
  }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  ordered_timesteps <- extract_timepoint_order(pi_vecs_cond)
  
  # Plot the timeseries with the pi vectors.
  value_multiplots <- timeseries_onset_plot(ts, pi_vecs, subs, runs)
  
  ordered_timeseries <- extract_ordered_timeseries(ts, ordered_timesteps)
  
  # calculate correlation based on the condition, where time points
  # that should see a higher response are factored in most
  cond_ts <- conditional_covariance(ordered_timeseries, rank=FALSE)
  cov_cond_ts <- cond_ts$cov
  mean_cond_ts <- cond_ts$mean
  
  overall_timeseries <- list(Relational=c(), Locational=c(), Overall=c())
  for (sub in names(ordered_timeseries)) {
    for (condition in names(ordered_timeseries[[sub]])) {
      overall_timeseries[[condition]] <- abind(overall_timeseries[[condition]],
                                               ordered_timeseries[[sub]][[condition]], along=1)
    }
  }
  
  overall_covariance <- sapply(overall_timeseries, function(condition) {
    cov(condition)
  }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  
  overall_mean <- sapply(overall_timeseries, function(condition) {
    apply(condition, 2, mean)
  }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  
  cov_cond_plots <- plot_condition_corr(cov_cond_ts, subs, runs)
  
  # reorder so that the conditions are our L1 keys, and subjects are L2
  cov_cond_reordered <- sapply(cond_key, function(cond) sapply(names(cov_cond_ts), function(sub) X =
                                                                cov_cond_ts[[sub]][[cond]],
                                                                USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE),
                                USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  
  ## Wilcoxon Tests ----------------------------------------------------------
  
  ranked_cov <- sapply(cov_cond_ts, function(sub) {
    sapply(sub, function(condition) {
      rank_matrix(condition)
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
  
  cov_wilcox <- wilcox_test_conditions(cov_cond_reordered, subs, runs)
  
  wilcox_plots <- plot_corr_wilcox(cov_wilcox, textsize=10)

We visualize first the covariance matrices for our respective conditions (note here that we consider the ranked covariance matrices):

We then can visualize the wilcoxon test results, where a low p-value indicates that a particular edge shows a difference in covariance for a particular condition when compared to the overall covariance. Note that we use the signed rank test, and not the related rank-sum test, since our data is paired (ie, we would expect some sort of dependence of our covariance values in the overall period compared to a particular condition since our overall period includes all of the observations of our particular condition periods).

Synthetic Data Construction

For our synthetic data construction, we will generate a synthetic model using our real data. For reference, the calculated covariance matrices are shown below, with their values ranked:

We begin with our Overall matrix, and use this to construct our conditional matrices for each condition. As we loop through our parameters, we replace values from our overall matrix increasingly with values from the specific condition’s matrix, ie, on the first round, we replace 0 of the elements, then replace the lowest 10% (lowest 10% of our p values from our wilcoxon tests), then replace the lowest 20%, and so on. In this fashion, we are replacing the edges of our covariance matrices with the most significant edges for noticing differences in covariance, and gradually replacing more and more until we have a covariance matrix equivalent to our condition’s matrix.

  source('C:/Users/ebrid/Documents/GitHub/Reliability/Code/FlashRupdated/functions/distance.R')
  source('C:/Users/ebrid/Documents/GitHub/Reliability/Code/FlashRupdated/functions/reliability.R')

  source('C:/Users/ebrid/Documents/GitHub/memory/Code/R/drivers/kde_dmtx.R')

  pvals <- seq(0, 1, .1)
  overall <- overall_covariance$Overall
  locational <- overall_covariance$Locational
  relational <- overall_covariance$Relational
  
  wilc_loc <- cov_wilcox$overall[[3]]
  wilc_rel <- cov_wilcox$overall[[2]]
  
  order_loc <- sort(wilc_loc, index.return=TRUE)$ix
  order_rel <- sort(wilc_rel, index.return=TRUE)$ix
  
  nt=283
  nroi = dim(overall)[2]
  for (p in pvals) {
    num_to_replace <- floor(p * length(order_loc))/2 # number of edges to replace this round
    
    syn_loc <- array(0, dim=dim(overall))
    syn_loc[order_loc[1:num_to_replace]] <- locational[order_loc[1:num_to_replace]]
    syn_loc <- syn_loc + t(syn_loc) - diag(diag(syn_loc))
    
    syn_loc[syn_loc == 0] = overall[syn_loc == 0]
    syn_loc <- syn_loc + ceiling(abs(min(eigen(syn_loc)$values)))*diag(nroi)
    
    syn_rel <- array(0, dim=dim(overall))
    syn_rel[order_rel[1:num_to_replace]] <- locational[order_rel[1:num_to_replace]]
    syn_rel <- syn_rel + t(syn_rel) - diag(diag(syn_rel))
    
    syn_rel[syn_rel == 0] = overall[syn_rel == 0]
    syn_rel <- syn_rel + ceiling(abs(min(eigen(syn_rel)$values)))*diag(nroi)
    
    # renormalize pi_vecs for each sub
    pi_vec_sub <- sapply(pi_vecs, function(sub) {
      t(apply(sub, 1, function(x) x/sum(x)))
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)

    require('MASS')
    latent_signal <- sapply(pi_vec_sub, function(sub_pi) {
      latent_sig <- array(0, dim=c(3, nt, nroi))

      latent_sig[1,,] <- mvrnorm(n=nt, mu=overall_mean$Relational, Sigma = syn_rel)
      latent_sig[2,,] <- mvrnorm(n=nt, mu=overall_mean$Locational, Sigma = syn_loc)
      latent_sig[3,,] <- mvrnorm(n=nt, mu=overall_mean$Overall, Sigma = overall)
      
      return(latent_sig)
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)

    observed_signal <- sapply(names(pi_vec_sub), function(sub) {
      sub_pi <- pi_vec_sub[[sub]]
      
      observed_signal <- t(sapply(1:dim(latent_signal[[sub]])[2], function(t) {
        apply(sub_pi[t,]*latent_signal[[sub]][,t,], 2, sum)
      }))
      return(observed_signal)
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
    
    true_means <- sapply(latent_signal, function(sub) {
      apply(sub, c(1,3), mean)
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
    
    true_cov <- sapply(latent_signal, function(sub) {
      sapply(1:dim(sub)[1], function(x) cov(sub[x,,]), simplify='array')
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
    
    predict_means <- array(0, dim=c(3, nroi))
    predict_means[1,] <- overall_mean$Relational
    predict_means[2,] <- overall_mean$Locational
    predict_means[3,] <- overall_mean$Overall
    
    predict_covs <- array(0, dim=c(nroi, nroi, 3))
    predict_covs[,,1] <- syn_rel
    predict_covs[,,2] <- syn_loc
    predict_covs[,,3] <- overall
    source('C:/Users/ebrid/Documents/GitHub/memory/code/R/experiments/gmm_known_pi.R')
    predict_params <- sapply(names(observed_signal), function(sub) {
      gmm_known_pi(observed_signal[[sub]], predict_means, predict_covs, pi_vec_sub[[sub]])
    }, USE.NAMES=TRUE, simplify=FALSE)
    
    result_mtx <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, nroi, length(names(predict_params))*3*2))
    id <- c()
    counter <- 1
    for (subject in names(predict_params)) {
      for (condition in 1:dim(predict_params[[subject]]$covs)[3]) {
        result_mtx[,,counter] = predict_params[[subject]]$covs[,,condition] #tGMM predictions
        result_mtx[,,counter + 1] = predict_covs[,,condition] # truths
        id <- c(id, subject, subject)
        counter = counter + 2 # increment...
      }
    }
    Dranked <- distance(rank_matrices(result_mtx))
    mnrranked <- mnr(rdf(Dranked, id))
    
    distance_title <- paste("Rewiring", p, "of the connections, discr = ", mnrranked)
    distance_plot <- ggplot(melt(Dranked), aes(x=Var1, y=Var2, fill=value)) + 
      geom_tile() +
      scale_fill_gradientn(colours=c("darkblue","blue","purple","green","yellow"),
                           name="distance") +
      xlab("Scan") + ylab("Scan") + ggtitle(distance_title) +
      theme(text=element_text(size=10))
    print(distance_plot)
  }

Reasons This Approach Isn’t working

There are probably two primary factors impacting why this method isn’t working.

  1. The differences we are trying to pick up on are very small. The different condition types have minute, albeit, very present (see wilcoxon results), differences in covariance. tGMM was somewhat consistent on the random datasets, however, those previously tested datasets were much more favorable in terms of the covariance differences between condition types. With conditions being relatively similar, this approach may not be favorable, as there is a lot of estimation involved and not a lot of wiggle room (only 300 time points, of which about 1/3 are time points for each condition respectively).

  2. There is a bug somewhere. There is inevitably a bug somewhere in this code; cramming a boatload of brand new methods in with classes doesn’t leave a lot of time to debug when I put together a massive new document. This week’s objectives will be to rerun the data with new atlases, and try and find bugs in what I’m currently doing, as right now, our previous method performs far better than the new one.
